docs.abstract: China, Russia, North Korea and Iran are relying on smuggling rings to secure equipment that can be used for weapons, satellites and fighter jets.
docs.snippet: China, Russia, North Korea and Iran are relying on smuggling rings to secure equipment that can be used for weapons, satellites and fighter jets.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Foreign smugglers are trying to ship advanced American technologies — which can be used for weapons and spy equipment — to China, Russia and other adversaries at rates that outpace shadowy and illegal exports during the Cold War, according to United States officials and experts.

headline.main: Smuggling of U.S. Technology Is Outpacing Cold War Levels, Experts Say
headline.print_headline: Smuggling of U.S. Technology Is Outpacing Cold War Levels, Experts Say

docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Adm. Karl L. Schultz was named the 26th commandant of the Coast Guard on Friday, taking over a military service that is in the midst of a fleet modernization as it juggles homeland security priorities like intercepting drugs and migrants and responding to disasters.

headline.main: Just in Time for Hurricane Season, a New Leader at the Coast Guard’s Helm

docs.abstract: The agency’s secretary, Kirstjen Nielsen, appeared to counter conclusions by the intelligence community that Moscow sought to give President Trump an edge in the 2016 election.
docs.snippet: The agency’s secretary, Kirstjen Nielsen, appeared to counter conclusions by the intelligence community that Moscow sought to give President Trump an edge in the 2016 election.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Kirstjen Nielsen, the homeland security secretary, said on Tuesday that she did not believe that Russia had tried to help President Trump during the 2016 election — putting her at odds with American intelligence agencies that found widespread meddling by Moscow.

headline.main: Homeland Security Chief Backtracks After Saying Russia Didn’t Try to Help Trump

docs.abstract: Border agents say the electronic searches have stopped terrorism suspects and criminals, but privacy advocates call them an invasive violation of the Constitution.
docs.snippet: Border agents say the electronic searches have stopped terrorism suspects and criminals, but privacy advocates call them an invasive violation of the Constitution.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Customs officers stationed at the American border and at airports searched an estimated 30,200 cellphones, computers and other electronic devices of people entering and leaving the United States last year — an almost 60 percent increase from 2016, according to Homeland Security Department data released on Friday.

headline.main: Cellphone and Computer Searches at U.S. Border Rise Under Trump
headline.print_headline: Searches Of Devices Increasing At Border

docs.abstract: The drop in apprehensions, to just over 42,500 people, follows weeks of chaos along the border amid the implementation of the Trump administration’s “zero tolerance” policy.
docs.snippet: The drop in apprehensions, to just over 42,500 people, follows weeks of chaos along the border amid the implementation of the Trump administration’s “zero tolerance” policy.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Federal immigration agents apprehended just over 42,500 people at the southwestern border in June, according to data released on Thursday by the Department of Homeland Security, a drop in the number of migrants trying to enter the United States after a spike the previous three months.

headline.main: Arrests at U.S.-Mexico Border Drop for First Time in Months
headline.print_headline: Arrests Drop At the Border For 1st Time In Months

docs.abstract: ICE special agents said the Trump administration’s crackdown on illegal migrants has hampered national security investigations and partnering with local officials.
docs.snippet: ICE special agents said the Trump administration’s crackdown on illegal migrants has hampered national security investigations and partnering with local officials.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — At least 19 Immigration and Customs Enforcement investigators are seeking to dissolve the agency, concerned that the Trump administration’s crackdown on illegal migrants has limited their ability to pursue national security threats, child pornography and transnational crime.

headline.main: Agents Seek to Dissolve ICE in Immigration Policy Backlash

docs.abstract: The transnational gang is a bit player compared with drug cartels. But its violence has helped the Trump administration sell its campaign against immigration.
docs.snippet: The transnational gang is a bit player compared with drug cartels. But its violence has helped the Trump administration sell its campaign against immigration.
docs.lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Early in his term, Attorney General Jeff Sessions instructed his top investigative deputies to target the transnational gang MS-13 as a priority. A year later, drug task forces have new powers to fight MS-13, more federal prosecutors are pursuing charges against the street gang with ties to El Salvador and foreign allies have been enlisted to capture its members.

headline.main: Trump Targets MS-13, a Violent Menace, if Not the One He Portrays
headline.print_headline: A Gang’s Fearsome Reputation,  Further Inflated by the President
